The wing patterns display a mottled texture, which is typical for seagulls, providing camouflage against the sandy beach environment. The wings are relatively broad and rounded at the tips, which is a common feature among gulls, aiding in their ability to glide efficiently over water.

The tail is short and slightly forked, another characteristic feature of many gull species. The size of the tail is proportionate to the overall body, neither overly long nor short, which is typical for many seabirds.
